---
import Layout from '@/components/astro/Layout.astro';
import { supabase } from '@/lib/supabase';

// Fetch real data
const { data: lobbyists } = await supabase
  .from('lobbyists')
  .select('*')
  .eq('is_active', true);

const totalLobbyists = lobbyists?.length || 0;
const claimedCount = lobbyists?.filter(l => l.is_claimed).length || 0;

const pageTitle = 'How to Become a Lobbyist in Texas: Complete Career Guide 2025';
const pageDescription = 'Texas lobbyist Byron Campbell reveals the real path to breaking into lobbying—from building relationships to landing your first client. What works, what doesn\'t, and what nobody tells you.';

const schema = {
  '@context': 'https://schema.org',
  '@type': 'Article',
  headline: pageTitle,
  description: pageDescription,
  author: {
    '@type': 'Person',
    name: 'Byron Campbell'
  },
  datePublished: '2025-01-08',
  dateModified: '2025-01-08',
};
---

<Layout title={pageTitle} description={pageDescription} schema={schema}>
  <!-- Hero Section -->
  <section class="bg-gradient-to-b from-texas-blue-50 via-white to-background py-20 lg:py-28 border-b border-border">
    <div class="container max-w-4xl">
      <div class="mb-8">
        <a
          href="/guides"
          class="inline-flex items-center text-sm font-medium text-texas-blue-600 hover:text-texas-blue-700 transition-colors group"
        >
          <svg class="w-4 h-4 mr-2 transition-transform group-hover:-translate-x-1" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24">
            <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M10 19l-7-7m0 0l7-7m-7 7h18" />
          </svg>
          Back to all guides
        </a>
      </div>

      <div class="inline-flex items-center rounded-full bg-texas-blue-500/10 px-4 py-2 text-sm font-medium text-texas-blue-700 mb-6">
        Career Guide
      </div>

      <h1 class="text-4xl md:text-5xl lg:text-6xl font-bold mb-6 leading-tight tracking-tight">
        How to Become a Lobbyist in Texas
      </h1>

      <p class="text-xl md:text-2xl text-muted-foreground mb-10 leading-relaxed max-w-3xl">
        Here's what nobody tells you about breaking into lobbying: you don't need a law degree, but you absolutely need relationships. This is the real roadmap—from your first Capitol job to landing clients who'll pay you to advocate.
      </p>

      <div class="flex flex-wrap gap-6 text-sm text-muted-foreground border-t border-border pt-6">
        <div class="flex items-center gap-2">
          <svg class="h-5 w-5 text-texas-blue-500" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24">
            <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M16 7a4 4 0 11-8 0 4 4 0 018 0zM12 14a7 7 0 00-7 7h14a7 7 0 00-7-7z" />
          </svg>
          <span class="font-medium">By Byron Campbell, Texas Lobbyist</span>
        </div>
        <div class="flex items-center gap-2">
          <svg class="h-5 w-5 text-texas-blue-500" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24">
            <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M12 8v4l3 3m6-3a9 9 0 11-18 0 9 9 0 0118 0z" />
          </svg>
          <span class="font-medium">15 min read</span>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Main Content -->
  <article class="py-16 lg:py-20">
    <div class="container max-w-3xl">

      <!-- Introduction -->
      <div class="prose prose-lg max-w-none mb-12">
        <p class="text-lg leading-relaxed">
          Let me start with the reality nobody wants to admit: the most successful lobbyist I know doesn't have a law degree, didn't serve in the Legislature, and spent her first five years at the Capitol making $32,000 a year as a committee clerk. What she did have was the cell phone numbers of every staffer who drafted education bills—and when she finally hung out her own shingle, those relationships were worth $200,000 in first-year contracts.
        </p>

        <p class="text-lg leading-relaxed">
          That's the formula for becoming a lobbyist in Texas: build relationships over years, develop expertise in policy areas that organizations care about, and eventually leverage those relationships into paying clients. The registration paperwork with the Texas Ethics Commission? That's the easy part. The hard part is the 3-5 years before anyone will pay you to advocate for them.
        </p>

        <p class="text-lg leading-relaxed">
          So let's talk about the real path—what works, what doesn't, and what I wish someone had told me when I was starting out.
        </p>
      </div>

      <!-- Reality Check -->
      <section id="reality-check" class="mb-16 scroll-mt-8">
        <div class="bg-red-50 border-l-4 border-red-500 rounded-r-lg p-6 mb-6">
          <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-2">What You Need to Hear First</h2>
          <p class="text-red-700 font-medium">This isn't a 6-month career pivot</p>
        </div>

        <div class="prose prose-lg max-w-none">
          <p>
            Before you invest years building toward a lobbying career, let's be honest about what this profession requires and whether it's right for you.
          </p>

          <div class="not-prose my-8">
            <div class="bg-red-50 border-2 border-red-300 rounded-lg p-6">
              <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-red-900 mb-4">This Career Path Requires:</h3>
              <div class="space-y-3 text-sm text-red-900">
                <div class="flex items-start gap-3">
                  <span class="text-red-600 font-bold flex-shrink-0 mt-0.5">→</span>
                  <div>
                    <strong>3-5 years minimum before you're marketable</strong> – You can't skip the relationship-building phase. Period.
                  </div>
                </div>
                <div class="flex items-start gap-3">
                  <span class="text-red-600 font-bold flex-shrink-0 mt-0.5">→</span>
                  <div>
                    <strong>Willingness to work underpaid Capitol jobs</strong> – Most entry points (legislative aide, committee staff, intern) pay $35K-$50K in expensive Austin.
                  </div>
                </div>
                <div class="flex items-start gap-3">
                  <span class="text-red-600 font-bold flex-shrink-0 mt-0.5">→</span>
                  <div>
                    <strong>Genuine enjoyment of relationship-building</strong> – If networking feels like pulling teeth, you'll hate this job.
                  </div>
                </div>
                <div class="flex items-start gap-3">
                  <span class="text-red-600 font-bold flex-shrink-0 mt-0.5">→</span>
                  <div>
                    <strong>Thick skin for rejection and uncertainty</strong> – Most bills die. Most asks get "no" or "not yet." You need resilience.
                  </div>
                </div>
                <div class="flex items-start gap-3">
                  <span class="text-red-600 font-bold flex-shrink-0 mt-0.5">→</span>
                  <div>
                    <strong>Unshakeable ethical standards</strong> – One ethics violation ends careers. You need the judgment to never cross lines.
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <p>
            Still interested? Good. Because Texas needs ethical, competent lobbyists who understand how to navigate the process without cutting corners. Let's talk about how you actually break in.
          </p>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- Career Paths -->
      <section id="career-paths" class="mb-16 scroll-mt-8">
        <div class="bg-texas-blue-50 border-l-4 border-texas-blue-500 rounded-r-lg p-6 mb-6">
          <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-2">Five Proven Paths to Lobbying</h2>
          <p class="text-texas-blue-700 font-medium">How successful Texas lobbyists got started</p>
        </div>

        <div class="prose prose-lg max-w-none">
          <p>
            There's no single path to becoming a lobbyist, but after watching hundreds of people enter this profession, I've seen five routes that consistently work. Notice what they all have in common: time spent inside the Capitol ecosystem building relationships.
          </p>

          <!-- Path 1: Legislative Staffer -->
          <div class="not-prose my-8">
            <div class="bg-gradient-to-br from-green-50 to-green-100 rounded-lg border-2 border-green-500 p-6">
              <div class="flex items-start gap-4">
                <div class="bg-green-600 text-white rounded-full w-12 h-12 flex items-center justify-center font-bold text-lg flex-shrink-0">1</div>
                <div class="flex-1">
                  <h3 class="text-xl font-bold mb-2">Legislative Staffer → Lobbyist</h3>
                  <div class="inline-flex items-center rounded-full bg-green-600 text-white px-3 py-1 text-xs font-medium mb-4">
                    MOST COMMON PATH
                  </div>
                  <p class="text-muted-foreground mb-4">
                    Spend 3-5 years working in a legislator's office or for a committee. Build relationships with members, other staffers, committee clerks, and advocates. Learn how bills move through the process. Eventually leverage those relationships into lobbying clients.
                  </p>

                  <div class="bg-white rounded-lg border border-green-300 p-4 mb-4">
                    <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-green-900 mb-2">Typical Career Timeline:</p>
                    <div class="space-y-2 text-sm text-green-900">
                      <div class="flex items-start gap-2">
                        <span class="font-bold">Year 1-2:</span>
                        <span>Session intern or junior legislative aide ($30K-$40K)</span>
                      </div>
                      <div class="flex items-start gap-2">
                        <span class="font-bold">Year 3-5:</span>
                        <span>Committee staff or senior policy advisor ($45K-$65K)</span>
                      </div>
                      <div class="flex items-start gap-2">
                        <span class="font-bold">Year 6+:</span>
                        <span>Transition to lobbying firm or independent practice</span>
                      </div>
                    </div>
                  </div>

                  <div class="bg-green-50 rounded-lg p-4 mb-4">
                    <p class="text-sm text-green-900">
                      <strong>Why this works:</strong> You're not just learning about the Legislature—you're becoming a trusted insider. The committee clerk who worked with you as a staffer will take your calls when you're a lobbyist. The members who relied on your bill analysis remember your competence. Those relationships are the foundation of your practice.
                    </p>
                  </div>

                  <div class="bg-white rounded-lg border border-green-300 p-4">
                    <p class="text-xs text-green-900">
                      <strong>Real example:</strong> Sarah started as an intern for the House Public Education Committee, became a full-time committee clerk, then moved to a member's office as education policy advisor. After five years, she launched her own practice focused exclusively on education lobbying. First-year revenue: $180K from three school district clients who valued her committee relationships.
                    </p>
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <!-- Path 2: State Agency -->
          <div class="not-prose my-8">
            <div class="bg-white rounded-lg border-2 border-blue-500 p-6">
              <div class="flex items-start gap-4">
                <div class="bg-blue-600 text-white rounded-full w-12 h-12 flex items-center justify-center font-bold text-lg flex-shrink-0">2</div>
                <div class="flex-1">
                  <h3 class="text-xl font-bold mb-2">State Agency → Lobbyist</h3>
                  <p class="text-muted-foreground mb-4">
                    Work at TCEQ, TxDOT, HHSC, Railroad Commission, or another major agency for 4-6 years. Build deep expertise in regulatory processes and relationships with legislators who oversee your agency. Transition to lobbying in your specialized policy area.
                  </p>

                  <div class="bg-blue-50 rounded-lg p-4 mb-4">
                    <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-blue-900 mb-2">Best Agencies for Lobbying Pipeline:</p>
                    <ul class="text-sm space-y-1 text-blue-900 ml-4">
                      <li>• <strong>TCEQ:</strong> Environmental and energy lobbying</li>
                      <li>• <strong>TxDOT:</strong> Transportation and infrastructure</li>
                      <li>• <strong>HHSC:</strong> Healthcare and Medicaid policy</li>
                      <li>• <strong>Railroad Commission:</strong> Oil and gas regulation</li>
                      <li>• <strong>TDLR:</strong> Professional licensing across industries</li>
                    </ul>
                  </div>

                  <div class="bg-white rounded-lg border border-blue-300 p-4">
                    <p class="text-sm text-blue-900">
                      <strong>Why this works:</strong> Regulatory expertise is extremely valuable, and you understand how agencies make decisions—knowledge most lobbyists lack. When you can explain the difference between a variance and a waiver, or how the rulemaking comment period works, clients pay premium rates for that expertise.
                    </p>
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <!-- Path 3: Trade Association -->
          <div class="not-prose my-8">
            <div class="bg-white rounded-lg border-2 border-purple-500 p-6">
              <div class="flex items-start gap-4">
                <div class="bg-purple-600 text-white rounded-full w-12 h-12 flex items-center justify-center font-bold text-lg flex-shrink-0">3</div>
                <div class="flex-1">
                  <h3 class="text-xl font-bold mb-2">Trade Association/Advocacy Org → Lobbyist</h3>
                  <p class="text-muted-foreground mb-4">
                    Work in government relations for an industry association or advocacy group. Represent organizational interests at the Capitol, build relationships with legislators and staff, develop policy expertise. Eventually go solo or join a lobbying firm.
                  </p>

                  <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-4 mb-4">
                    <div class="bg-purple-50 rounded-lg p-4">
                      <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-purple-900 mb-2">Advantages:</p>
                      <ul class="text-xs space-y-1 text-purple-900 ml-4">
                        <li>• Already lobbying, just as employee</li>
                        <li>• Build credibility in specific industry</li>
                        <li>• Develop coalition relationships</li>
                        <li>• Learn legislative process hands-on</li>
                      </ul>
                    </div>
                    <div class="bg-purple-50 rounded-lg p-4">
                      <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-purple-900 mb-2">Challenges:</p>
                      <ul class="text-xs space-y-1 text-purple-900 ml-4">
                        <li>• Non-compete clauses with former employer</li>
                        <li>• Potential conflicts with industry clients</li>
                        <li>• Need to prove broader expertise</li>
                        <li>• Transition from advocate to consultant</li>
                      </ul>
                    </div>
                  </div>

                  <div class="bg-white rounded-lg border border-purple-300 p-4">
                    <p class="text-sm text-purple-900">
                      <strong>Why this works:</strong> You're already lobbying—you've testified at hearings, worked with coalition partners, built relationships with key legislators on relevant committees. The transition to independent lobbying is natural, though you'll need to navigate non-compete restrictions carefully.
                    </p>
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <!-- Path 4: Former Legislator -->
          <div class="not-prose my-8">
            <div class="bg-white rounded-lg border-2 border-orange-500 p-6">
              <div class="flex items-start gap-4">
                <div class="bg-orange-600 text-white rounded-full w-12 h-12 flex items-center justify-center font-bold text-lg flex-shrink-0">4</div>
                <div class="flex-1">
                  <h3 class="text-xl font-bold mb-2">Former Legislator → Lobbyist</h3>
                  <p class="text-muted-foreground mb-4">
                    Serve in the Texas House or Senate for 2-6+ terms, then transition to lobbying using insider knowledge and relationships with former colleagues.
                  </p>

                  <div class="bg-orange-50 border border-orange-300 rounded-lg p-4 mb-4">
                    <p class="text-sm text-orange-900 mb-2">
                      <strong>Built-in advantages:</strong> Direct relationships with current members, deep understanding of parliamentary procedure, name recognition, instant credibility with clients who want "insider access."
                    </p>
                  </div>

                  <div class="bg-red-50 border border-red-300 rounded-lg p-4 mb-4">
                    <p class="text-sm text-red-900 mb-2">
                      <strong>Common failure modes:</strong> Some former legislators struggle with the transition because they can't adapt to being the petitioner instead of the decision-maker. The skills that make you a successful legislator (constituent relations, coalition-building, media presence) don't always translate to effective lobbying.
                    </p>
                  </div>

                  <div class="bg-white rounded-lg border border-orange-300 p-4">
                    <p class="text-xs text-orange-900">
                      <strong>The honest answer:</strong> Former legislators often command premium rates ($15K-$30K+/month retainers) for high-profile clients, but they're also competing against other former members and face higher expectations. Being a former legislator opens doors—but you still need to deliver strategic value, not just access.
                    </p>
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <!-- Path 5: Campaign Experience -->
          <div class="not-prose my-8">
            <div class="bg-white rounded-lg border-2 border-amber-500 p-6">
              <div class="flex items-start gap-4">
                <div class="bg-amber-600 text-white rounded-full w-12 h-12 flex items-center justify-center font-bold text-lg flex-shrink-0">5</div>
                <div class="flex-1">
                  <h3 class="text-xl font-bold mb-2">Campaign Operative → Lobbyist</h3>
                  <p class="text-muted-foreground mb-4">
                    Run campaigns for legislative or statewide candidates, build relationships with elected officials and their teams, develop political instincts, transition to lobbying leveraging those connections.
                  </p>

                  <div class="bg-amber-50 rounded-lg p-4 mb-4">
                    <p class="text-sm text-amber-900">
                      <strong>Why this can work:</strong> Campaign staff build intense relationships with candidates who become legislators. If you ran someone's campaign and they won, you have credibility and access. The challenge is translating campaign skills (messaging, voter outreach, fundraising) into lobbying skills (policy expertise, coalition management, legislative strategy).
                    </p>
                  </div>

                  <div class="bg-white rounded-lg border border-amber-300 p-4">
                    <p class="text-sm text-amber-900">
                      <strong>The transition:</strong> Most successful campaign-to-lobbying transitions involve working as a legislative aide first to learn the policy and process side, then leveraging both campaign relationships AND legislative experience into a lobbying practice.
                    </p>
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="not-prose bg-green-50 border-l-4 border-green-500 rounded-r-lg p-6 my-8">
            <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-green-900 mb-2">The Capitol Intern Fast Track</h3>
            <p class="text-sm text-green-900">
              Here's the secret path nobody talks about: start as a Capitol intern during session. It's 5 months of low pay or unpaid work, but you'll meet 100+ legislators, staffers, and advocates. You'll see how bills actually move. You'll build relationships that take others years to develop. If you're young enough and can afford it financially, this is the fastest way to break into the Capitol ecosystem. Half the successful lobbyists I know started as interns.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- Skills Required -->
      <section id="skills" class="mb-16 scroll-mt-8">
        <div class="bg-texas-blue-50 border-l-4 border-texas-blue-500 rounded-r-lg p-6 mb-6">
          <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-2">Essential Skills You Need to Develop</h2>
          <p class="text-texas-blue-700 font-medium">What separates successful lobbyists from struggling ones</p>
        </div>

        <div class="prose prose-lg max-w-none">
          <p>
            Anyone can register as a lobbyist. But effectiveness requires a specific skillset that takes years to develop. Here's what you need to master:
          </p>

          <div class="not-prose my-8 space-y-4">
            <div class="bg-white border-l-4 border-texas-blue-500 rounded-r-lg p-6">
              <h3 class="text-lg font-bold mb-3">Relationship Intelligence</h3>
              <p class="text-sm text-muted-foreground mb-3">
                Not just knowing people, but understanding power dynamics—who actually controls decisions, which staffers draft the amendments, who influences whom, and how to navigate complex political relationships without burning bridges.
              </p>
              <div class="bg-blue-50 rounded-lg p-4">
                <p class="text-xs text-blue-900">
                  <strong>What this looks like:</strong> You know that the committee chair's senior policy advisor has more influence over bill language than the chair himself. You understand that the budget analyst who's been there 15 years knows where every body is buried. You've learned which legislative directors control their member's calendar and which don't. This knowledge only comes from years inside the system.
                </p>
              </div>
            </div>

            <div class="bg-white border-l-4 border-green-500 rounded-r-lg p-6">
              <h3 class="text-lg font-bold mb-3">Strategic Patience</h3>
              <p class="text-sm text-muted-foreground mb-3">
                Knowing when to push hard and when to back off. Understanding that losing this session might position you to win next session. Playing long-term games in a short-term political environment.
              </p>
              <div class="bg-green-50 rounded-lg p-4">
                <p class="text-xs text-green-900">
                  <strong>Real application:</strong> Last session, I advised a client to let their bill die in committee rather than forcing an ugly floor fight. Why? Because the committee chair promised to carry our bill FIRST next session if we didn't embarrass him this time. We waited. Next session, our bill passed unanimously. Strategic patience pays.
                </p>
              </div>
            </div>

            <div class="bg-white border-l-4 border-purple-500 rounded-r-lg p-6">
              <h3 class="text-lg font-bold mb-3">Deep Policy Expertise</h3>
              <p class="text-sm text-muted-foreground mb-3">
                Understanding not just bill text, but legislative history, regulatory context, budget implications, and political dynamics. Becoming the subject matter expert legislators call when they need background.
              </p>
              <div class="bg-purple-50 rounded-lg p-4">
                <p class="text-xs text-purple-900">
                  <strong>How to build this:</strong> Pick 2-3 policy areas and go deep. Read every bill filed in those areas. Attend every hearing. Write analysis. Speak at conferences. Within 3-5 years, you should know more about your policy area than 90% of legislators. That expertise is what clients pay for.
                </p>
              </div>
            </div>

            <div class="bg-white border-l-4 border-orange-500 rounded-r-lg p-6">
              <h3 class="text-lg font-bold mb-3">Coalition Management</h3>
              <p class="text-sm text-muted-foreground mb-3">
                Getting organizations with competing interests to work together requires diplomatic skill, conflict resolution, and the ability to find common ground without compromising anyone's core positions.
              </p>
              <div class="bg-orange-50 rounded-lg p-4">
                <p class="text-xs text-orange-900">
                  <strong>The skill in practice:</strong> You need to get the hospitals, the doctors, and the insurance companies to agree on healthcare legislation—groups that usually fight each other. How? Find the narrow area of genuine alignment, craft language that serves everyone's minimum needs, and keep egos out of the room. It's harder than it sounds.
                </p>
              </div>
            </div>

            <div class="bg-white border-l-4 border-red-500 rounded-r-lg p-6">
              <h3 class="text-lg font-bold mb-3">Unshakeable Ethics</h3>
              <p class="text-sm text-muted-foreground mb-3">
                Knowing where the ethical lines are and never crossing them—even when it would be easy or profitable. Your reputation is your only real asset in this business.
              </p>
              <div class="bg-red-50 rounded-lg p-4">
                <p class="text-xs text-red-900">
                  <strong>Why this matters more than anything:</strong> One ethics violation ends careers. I've watched lobbyists lose everything—clients, reputation, registration—because they cut a corner or crossed a line. The temptation exists constantly. The pressure from clients is real. You need the ethical judgment to say no when asked to do something questionable, even if it costs you a contract.
                </p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- Building Network -->
      <section id="network" class="mb-16 scroll-mt-8">
        <div class="bg-texas-blue-50 border-l-4 border-texas-blue-500 rounded-r-lg p-6 mb-6">
          <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-2">Building Your Capitol Network</h2>
          <p class="text-texas-blue-700 font-medium">Your relationships literally ARE your net worth</p>
        </div>

        <div class="prose prose-lg max-w-none">
          <p>
            Let's be completely direct about this: <strong>lobbying is a relationship business.</strong> Your network isn't just important—it's literally the foundation of your entire practice. Without relationships, you're just an expensive Google alert service.
          </p>

          <p>
            You need relationships with legislators, chiefs of staff, committee clerks, agency heads, other lobbyists, industry leaders, and Capitol reporters. The more people who know, trust, and respect you, the more effective—and valuable—you become to clients.
          </p>

          <div class="not-prose my-8 bg-gradient-to-br from-blue-50 to-blue-100 rounded-lg border-2 border-blue-500 p-6">
            <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-blue-900 mb-4">The Relationship Tiers (From Most to Least Valuable)</h3>

            <div class="space-y-3">
              <div class="bg-white rounded-lg p-4">
                <div class="flex items-start gap-3">
                  <div class="bg-blue-600 text-white rounded-full w-8 h-8 flex items-center justify-center font-bold text-sm flex-shrink-0">1</div>
                  <div class="flex-1">
                    <p class="font-bold text-sm text-blue-900 mb-1">Personal Cell Phone Access</p>
                    <p class="text-xs text-blue-800">Committee chairs, leadership staff, senior advisors who'll take your call at 9 PM when bills are being amended. This takes 5-10 years to build. Worth its weight in gold.</p>
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>

              <div class="bg-white rounded-lg p-4">
                <div class="flex items-start gap-3">
                  <div class="bg-blue-600 text-white rounded-full w-8 h-8 flex items-center justify-center font-bold text-sm flex-shrink-0">2</div>
                  <div class="flex-1">
                    <p class="font-bold text-sm text-blue-900 mb-1">Chief of Staff Direct Lines</p>
                    <p class="text-xs text-blue-800">The people who control member schedules and advise on vote decisions. If they trust you, they'll make time for your issues.</p>
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>

              <div class="bg-white rounded-lg p-4">
                <div class="flex items-start gap-3">
