                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="not-prose bg-red-50 border-2 border-red-400 rounded-lg p-6 my-8">
            <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-red-900 mb-3">Critical: Read the Ethics Commission's Complete Guide</h3>
            <p class="text-sm text-red-900 mb-3">
              Registration is straightforward, but Texas lobbying law has specific requirements around gifts, expenditures, reporting deadlines, and prohibited conduct. Download and read the Texas Ethics Commission's complete lobbying guide before you register.
            </p>
            <p class="text-sm text-red-900 font-bold">
              One ethics violation can end your career. Know the rules. Follow them exactly. When in doubt, ask the Ethics Commission for guidance—they provide advisory opinions.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- Landing First Client -->
      <section id="first-client" class="mb-16 scroll-mt-8">
        <div class="bg-green-50 border-l-4 border-green-500 rounded-r-lg p-6 mb-6">
          <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-2">Landing Your First Client</h2>
          <p class="text-green-700 font-medium">The hardest step—and what actually works</p>
        </div>

        <div class="prose prose-lg max-w-none">
          <p>
            You've got Capitol experience. You've built relationships. You understand the process. Now you need someone to pay you. This is where most aspiring lobbyists struggle—and where many give up.
          </p>

          <p>
            The reality is brutal: nobody hands you clients. You have to earn them by demonstrating value and leveraging relationships. Here's what works:
          </p>

          <div class="not-prose my-8 space-y-6">
            <!-- Strategy 1 -->
            <div class="bg-white rounded-lg border-2 border-green-500 p-6">
              <div class="flex items-start gap-4">
                <div class="bg-green-600 text-white rounded-full w-12 h-12 flex items-center justify-center font-bold text-lg flex-shrink-0">1</div>
                <div class="flex-1">
                  <h4 class="text-lg font-bold mb-3">Leverage Your Former Employer (Carefully)</h4>
                  <p class="text-sm text-muted-foreground mb-4">
                    Worked for a legislator? Companies that care about that member's committee will value your relationship. Worked at TCEQ? Environmental firms need your regulatory expertise. Your previous position is your first marketing pitch.
                  </p>
                  <div class="bg-muted rounded-lg p-4 mb-4">
                    <p class="text-xs font-semibold mb-2">How to position yourself:</p>
                    <p class="text-xs text-muted-foreground">
                      "For five years I was senior policy advisor to the Chair of House Public Education. I know every member of that committee personally, understand their priorities, and have relationships with the committee staff who draft education bills. If your organization has education priorities in Texas, I can help you navigate that committee effectively."
