        <div class="prose prose-lg max-w-none">
          <p>
            I've watched promising lobbying careers implode over mistakes that were completely avoidable. Here are the errors that will end your career before it starts—or destroy a successful practice you spent years building.
          </p>

          <div class="not-prose my-8 space-y-4">
            <div class="bg-red-50 border-2 border-red-400 rounded-lg p-6">
              <div class="flex items-start gap-3">
                <div class="text-red-600 text-2xl font-bold flex-shrink-0">×</div>
                <div class="flex-1">
                  <h4 class="text-lg font-bold text-red-900 mb-2">Ethics Violations (Career Ending—Zero Tolerance)</h4>
                  <p class="text-sm text-red-900 mb-3">
                    One ethics violation ends careers. Period. No second chances. Filing late reports, improper gift disclosures, quid pro quo arrangements, failing to register—any of these can result in fines, loss of registration, and permanent reputation damage.
                  </p>
                  <div class="bg-red-100 rounded-lg p-3">
                    <p class="text-xs text-red-900">
                      <strong>What this looks like:</strong> A lobbyist forgets to file a quarterly report on time. Gets fined. The news shows up in Ethics Commission records. Potential clients Google them and see the violation. They never get a callback. That's how careers end.
                    </p>
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>

            <div class="bg-red-50 border-2 border-red-400 rounded-lg p-6">
              <div class="flex items-start gap-3">
                <div class="text-red-600 text-2xl font-bold flex-shrink-0">×</div>
                <div class="flex-1">
                  <h4 class="text-lg font-bold text-red-900 mb-2">Burning Bridges (Texas Politics Is a Small World)</h4>
                  <p class="text-sm text-red-900 mb-3">
                    The staffer you're rude to today might be a committee chair in 10 years. The lobbyist you undercut might be hiring at the best firm when you need a job. The reporter you mislead will remember—and write about it.
                  </p>
                  <div class="bg-red-100 rounded-lg p-3">
                    <p class="text-xs text-red-900">
                      <strong>The rule:</strong> Be professional always. Even when you're frustrated. Even when someone is being unreasonable. Even when you think it doesn't matter. It always matters eventually. Relationships are your only real asset—protect them obsessively.
                    </p>
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>

            <div class="bg-red-50 border-2 border-red-400 rounded-lg p-6">
              <div class="flex items-start gap-3">
                <div class="text-red-600 text-2xl font-bold flex-shrink-0">×</div>
                <div class="flex-1">
                  <h4 class="text-lg font-bold text-red-900 mb-2">Over-Promising Results (Credibility Destruction)</h4>
                  <p class="text-sm text-red-900 mb-3">
                    Never guarantee a bill will pass or promise outcomes you can't control. The client who hires you because you "guaranteed" passage will destroy your reputation when the bill inevitably faces unexpected opposition and dies.
                  </p>
                  <div class="bg-red-100 rounded-lg p-3">
                    <p class="text-xs text-red-900">
                      <strong>The right approach:</strong> "Based on current dynamics, I believe we have a strong chance of passage if X, Y, and Z factors break our way. I can position us optimally, but I can't control all variables." Under-promise, over-deliver. Always.
                    </p>
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>

            <div class="bg-red-50 border-2 border-red-400 rounded-lg p-6">
              <div class="flex items-start gap-3">
                <div class="text-red-600 text-2xl font-bold flex-shrink-0">×</div>
                <div class="flex-1">
                  <h4 class="text-lg font-bold text-red-900 mb-2">Being Overly Partisan (Limits Your Effectiveness)</h4>
                  <p class="text-sm text-red-900 mb-3">
                    Effective lobbyists work across party lines. If you alienate half the Legislature with partisan rhetoric or exclusively work one side of the aisle, you limit your client potential and effectiveness.
                  </p>
                  <div class="bg-red-100 rounded-lg p-3">
                    <p class="text-xs text-red-900">
                      <strong>The strategic approach:</strong> Build relationships with members of both parties. Demonstrate you can work with anyone on policy substance. Clients hire you to solve problems, not validate their political preferences.
                    </p>
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>

            <div class="bg-red-50 border-2 border-red-400 rounded-lg p-6">
              <div class="flex items-start gap-3">
                <div class="text-red-600 text-2xl font-bold flex-shrink-0">×</div>
                <div class="flex-1">
                  <h4 class="text-lg font-bold text-red-900 mb-2">Lying to Legislators or Staff (Trust Destruction)</h4>
                  <p class="text-sm text-red-900 mb-3">
                    Provide bad information—even once—and you'll never be trusted again. Legislators and staff have long memories. They track which lobbyists give them accurate information and which ones spin or mislead.
                  </p>
                  <div class="bg-red-100 rounded-lg p-3">
                    <p class="text-xs text-red-900">
                      <strong>The standard:</strong> Always be truthful. If you don't know something, say "I don't know, let me research that and get back to you." If the facts don't support your client's position, find a better argument or advise them the fight isn't winnable. Never lie.
                    </p>
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

